SIMPLE: stark
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stark
<hw>Stark</hw> <pr>(st⟦aum⟧rk)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Starker</adjf> <pr>(-⟦etil⟧r)</pr>;
<pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Starkest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stark</ets> stiff, strong, AS. <ets>stearc</ets>; akin to OS.
<ets>starc</ets> strong, D. <ets>sterk</ets>, OHG. <ets>starc</ets>,
<ets>starah</ets>, G. & Sw. <ets>stark</ets>, Dan. <ets>staerk</ets>,
Icel. <ets>sterkr</ets>, Goth. ga<ets>sta⟦uacute⟧rknan</ets> to become
dried up, Lith. <ets>str⟦eum⟧gti</ets> to stiffen, to freeze. Cf.
<er>Starch</er>, <pos>a.</pos> & <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Stiff; rigid.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose senses all were straight benumbed and <qex>stark</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His heart gan wax as <qex>stark</qex> as marble stone.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many a nobleman lies <qex>stark</qex> and stiff⟦br⟧
Under the hoofs of vaunting enemies.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The north is not so <qex>stark</qex> and cold.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Complete; absolute; full; perfect; entire.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Consider the <qex>stark</qex> security⟦br⟧
The common wealth is in now.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Strong; vigorous; powerful.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>stark</qex>, moss-trooping Scot.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Stark</qex> beer, boy, stout and strong beer.</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Severe; violent; fierce.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧In <xex>starke</xex> stours⟦rdquo⟧ [<it>i. e.</it>, in fierce
combats]. <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Mere; sheer; gross; entire; downright.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He pronounces the citation <qex>stark</qex> nonsense.</q>
<rj><qau>Collier.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rhetoric is very good or <qex>stark</qex> naught; there's no
medium in rhetoric.</q> <rj><qau>Selden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stark</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stark
<hw>Stark</hw> <pr>(st⟦aum⟧rk)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Wholly;
entirely; absolutely; quite; <as>as, <ex>stark</ex> mad</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Held him strangled in his arms till he was <qex>stark</qex>
dead.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stark naked</b></col>, <cd>wholly naked; quite
bare.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Strip your sword <qex>stark naked</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ According to Professor Skeat,
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>stark-naked</xex>⟦rdquo⟧ is derived from
<xex>steort-naked</xex>, or <xex>start-naked</xex>, literally
<xex>tail-naked</xex>, and hence <xex>wholly naked</xex>. If this
etymology be true the preferable form is
<xex>stark-naked</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stark</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stark
<hw>Stark</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To stiffen.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If horror have not <qex>starked</qex> your limbs.</q> <rj><qau>H.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Starkly</ent>⟦br⟧
